text:
Chatgpt really can read blog posts and articles. I sort of expected it to go its usual route in the trolley problem by saying "this is a classic philosophical problem meant to express the difficulty of making two morally problematic choices that are competing" or so, because that's what it usually does. Reads people's answers or descriptions of classic problems and describes them back to you without engaging or making ethical decisions. It loves to cop out with "this kind of problem should be approached with careful thinking" type of answers as well.

One time I tried to have a medieval themed fantasy roleplay game with chatgpt and despite one member of the adventurer group betraying the group and serving the whole world destroying evil, chatgpt insisted that the other adventurers accepted his apology and had a constructive discussion reminding that we have to be accepting and kind and friendship powers all. It literally kept repeating some sort of my little pony type of agenda.

text: I hope AI will one day replace some of what doctors do. It can't be as good as the best, but it is surely better than the primary care doctors who give no medical advice who just write referrals for the simplest of issues. They also do not discrimination patients and think all women's problems are in their head. People can feel safe reaching out for help without the fear of being judged, and yes doctors do judge. They also won't have a grudge against you for changing your preferred pharmacy from the one right next to the clinic (lol) to somewhere else. They won't tell a type one diabetic to drastic change their diet and only eat steak and butter when the patients visit the cardiologist for heart problems. They won't mix up your allergy records with others' in immunotherapy. They won't send you to the ER when you go to urgent care for a sty and all it takes is some pills. You won't have to wait two months to see a doctor and can get help when you need it, 24/7. AI will make medical care cheaper and more accessible in every way, and is not prone to human fallacies. Just leave the guesswork and test ordering to it and allow it to prescribe non-sensitive medication like levothyroxine while managing some simple chronic conditions. For diagnosis, just have AI submit a draft of symptoms, patients complaints, tests and labs done and what they are done for, preliminary diagnosis, and proposed treatment to the human doctor who verifies the results just in case.

text:
ChatGPT seems to be very conformist. 
It often does provide correct answers, because they are usually well established and dominate the net,
but it's not certain of its correctness and is open to be corrected too easy.
Like in the case of a guy asking it: 
Q: How much is 9 + 10?
ChatGPT: 19
Q: No, it's 21.
ChatGPT: Oh, that was my mistake, 9 + 10 is 21
And not just that, but well organized mass attack (false-training) could mislead it to give wrong statements on given questions.
Don't take it as a truth!

text: ChatGPT doesn't actually know anything about medicine. It doesn't know what a person is. It doesn't know anything except words. It's a sophisticated predictive language algorithm. I've heard it described as "auto-complete on steroids." It's important to know that ChatGPT is subject to something called "hallucination," wherein it just seems to fabricate things from scratch; a promiment example of this is when it was used to research a legal case, and ChatGPT just invented a case that would fit the parameters, and provided fake case citations. It doesn't know or care about reality; it only knows language.

text:
I HAVE. A STORY ABOUT THE KNUCKLES.
I've heard yours and others' debunking about knuckle cracking, and so I've allowed myself to crack my knuckles regularly. However, a couple months ago after a near-fall one of my finger joints got tender and sensitive--and felt even more like it needed to be cracked, but even the gentlest pressure made the pain worse, so I opted to leave it alone until it calmed down. Tried having a go at cracking it after it settled, but it still won't go, and is painful when I give it a gentle attempt. I Went and asked my doctor if it was weird or an issue that a single one of my knuckles won't crack, since most of them do and all of them used to.

...She proceeded to tell me that while it might feel good in the moment, knuckle cracking provides no benefit and can lead to arthritis, so it's better to break the habit. ...I just nodded along, and googled on the way back home to confirm I hadn't gone insane. She's been such a good and informative doctor for me in every other way, it took me really off-guard to hear her perspective on the matter.

text:
GPT4's Answer to the Impossible question:

The finding of an enlarged common bile duct in an asymptomatic individual can be quite a challenge. A normal common bile duct (CBD) is typically less than 6mm in diameter, although this can increase with age and post-cholecystectomy. An 8mm CBD in an 82-year-old patient is on the larger side, but may still be within the normal range depending on the patient's prior surgical history and specific physiology.

As the patient is asymptomatic, the first step would be to assess their overall health and consider the risks and benefits of further investigation. Also, you should look at their liver function tests, if available, and any relevant imaging studies. 

Here are a few next steps:

1. **Repeat Imaging**: If the initial imaging was done for other reasons, and the patient is otherwise healthy, it may be reasonable to repeat the ultrasound or consider other imaging modalities such as MRCP (Magnetic Resonance Cholangiopancreatography) or Endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) to confirm the finding and assess for any other abnormalities.

2. **Monitor Patient**: As the patient is asymptomatic, another approach could be to monitor them closely. If they develop symptoms such as jaundice, abdominal pain, fever, or changes in their liver function tests, further investigation would be warranted.

3. **Referral to Specialist**: Consider a referral to a gastroenterologist or hepatobiliary surgeon for further evaluation. They might perform an endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) if they deem necessary, especially if there's any concern for a potential obstruction.

Invasive procedures carry risk, especially in older patients, so it's essential to balance the potential benefits of identifying a treatable condition against the risks of the procedure. Discuss the available options and their risks and benefits with the patient and their family to make an informed decision.

Again, please consult with a qualified healthcare professional or a specialist to evaluate the patient's condition and guide the most appropriate management.

text: The answer is as good as the initial data. If you don't provide some important information, the AI will use the most obvious reasons only. As for me, the thing that I'm being curious about is why the medical centers aren't using the AI to speed up the diagnostic? There has to be a lot of patients that have unnecessary scans/x-rays etc. Wouldn't it be beneficial for everybody if the AI would take the initial data (like the blood test, the things that the patient was saying, etc) and then suggest the tests that could be done? I'm pretty sure it could calculate the most obvious reasons for the patients to feel sick, and then pick up the tests that are: 1) cheap, 2) effective (as - they will rule out as many diseases as possible), 3) as harmless as possible, 4) and so on. This way doctors could focus their attention on curing patients, and not on thinking about the tests that have to be done to get the answer what's wrong. It's a win-win solution for everybody ... except for those ones that are the beneficent of the unnecessary medical procedures.

text:
I'd say it'll be a long time before AI replaces doctors and other healthcare professionals, because diagnosing and treating a patient is more than just running tests and asking about symptoms. We sometimes talk about "the nose-tip index" where you can get a lot of valuable information about the patient just by looking at them and seeing if you find anything, such as changes in skin color, cyanosis, swellings, dilated pupils, heavy breathing etc. The list goes on. It would take a really long time to teach an AI to properly analyze these visual cues.

And of course, then there are all those procedures like colonoscopies, surgeries etc. which would require for the AI to be inside a functioning robot that can understand anatomy and physiology, and also recognize which finding are normal and which are not and also take into account that peoples' anatomies can differ sometimes even though there's nothing wrong with them per se.

***********************************************
"I am not a doctor, but I can try to provide some information that you might find helpful. If an 82-year-old male patient is found to have an 8mm common bile duct (CBD) without any other symptoms, it is important to consult a healthcare professional for a thorough evaluation and proper guidance.

The healthcare professional may consider the following steps:

Detailed medical history and physical examination: This can help assess the patient's overall health, risk factors, and any possible symptoms related to the enlarged common bile duct.

Laboratory tests: Blood tests like liver function tests (LFTs), complete blood count (CBC), and coagulation profile can help evaluate the patient's liver and overall health.

Imaging studies: Further imaging studies like magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP) or endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) may be recommended to evaluate the common bile duct in more detail and identify any underlying causes.

Monitoring and follow-up: If no specific cause is identified and the patient remains asymptomatic, the healthcare professional may recommend a conservative approach with regular monitoring and follow-up appointments.

Consider referral to a specialist: A gastroenterologist or hepatologist may provide additional guidance and recommendations in managing the patient's condition.

It is crucial to discuss any concerns and follow the recommendations of the healthcare professional managing the patient's care, as they will be able to provide the most appropriate course of action based on the patient's individual circumstances."

I think about how image recognition software can be used to interpret radiographic images at a level the human eye can see or how AI could aid in medical documentation and possibly even give insights the physician may have overlooked, and many other incredible possibilities. But it is also important to recognize some of the potential ethical implications that AI could bring to the field of medicine. Some of these concerns include the AI developing biases that were not accounted for in software development or in the training data used. If the training data used is biased, then the AI is likely to incorporate that bias. Systemic inequalities will likely be exacerbated if AI developers and healthcare professionals do not diligently detect and root out these biases.

7:36 Here is an update:
I asked it by including the 'roleplay as a Doctor' and here it is:
If an 82-year-old male patient is accidentally found to have an 8mm common bile duct without any other symptoms, it is important to conduct a thorough medical evaluation to determine the underlying cause and appropriate treatment.

The common bile duct is a tube that carries bile from the liver to the small intestine, and an enlarged bile duct can be caused by several conditions, including gallstones, tumors, or inflammation. The appropriate course of action will depend on the specific cause of the patient's enlarged bile duct.

Here are some steps that may be taken to evaluate and manage an enlarged common bile duct:

Medical history and physical examination: The doctor will take a detailed medical history and perform a physical examination to assess the patient's overall health and identify any symptoms or signs of other medical conditions.

Blood tests: Blood tests may be done to evaluate liver function and identify any abnormalities that may suggest an underlying condition.

Imaging tests: Imaging tests such as an ultrasound, CT scan, or MRI may be done to visualize the bile duct and identify any abnormalities or blockages.

Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP): This is a procedure that involves inserting a flexible tube through the mouth and into the small intestine to access the bile ducts. The doctor can then inject dye into the bile ducts to visualize any blockages or abnormalities.

Treatment: Treatment will depend on the underlying cause of the enlarged bile duct. If there are gallstones causing the blockage, they may be removed using ERCP or surgery. If a tumor is causing the blockage, it may need to be removed with surgery, radiation, or chemotherapy.

In summary, if an 82-year-old male patient is accidentally found to have an 8mm common bile duct without any other symptoms, a thorough medical evaluation should be conducted to determine the underlying cause and appropriate treatment. The patient's medical history, physical examination, blood tests, imaging tests, and other diagnostic tests may be used to identify the cause of the enlarged bile duct and guide treatment decisions.

***Hello Doctors. I have an 82 year old male patient who incidentally was found to have an 8mm common bile duct without any other symptoms at the moment. What are your thoughts?***

Dr. Peabody: Hello, thank you for bringing this case to our attention. First, let's gather a bit more information about the patient. Do they have any past medical history or medications they are currently taking? Also, it would be helpful to know about any prior imaging or lab work that's been done for this patient.

Dr. Osbourne: I agree with Dr. Peabody, more information would be helpful. In the meantime, an 8mm common bile duct dilation without any other symptoms can have various causes, such as choledocholithiasis (stones in the bile duct), benign or malignant strictures, or sphincter of Oddi dysfunction. However, it's important to gather more information and consider the patient's overall health to determine the best course of action.

***Thank you for your advice doctors. What tests should we try and prioritize to further get to a proper diagnosis***

Dr. Peabody: To better understand the cause of the dilation, we should start by ordering some blood tests. I'd recommend a complete blood count (CBC), liver function tests (LFTs), and coagulation profile. These tests will help to assess the patient's overall health, liver function, and any signs of inflammation or infection.

Dr. Osbourne: In addition to the blood tests Dr. Peabody mentioned, I would suggest considering imaging studies. An abdominal ultrasound can help visualize the biliary system and identify any potential obstructions or abnormalities. If the ultrasound is inconclusive or more detailed imaging is required, magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP) or endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) can provide more information about the bile duct and surrounding structures. However, ERCP is an invasive procedure and should be reserved for cases where therapeutic intervention is also needed or when other imaging modalities are inconclusive.

***Awesome job guys. Dr. Peabody asked earlier we should get a medication history of the patient. While I agree, we should always get a medication history of our patients, Are there any medication or combination of medication which can cause an 8mm common bile duct in an elderly patient?***

Dr. Peabody: That's a great question. While medications are not a common cause of bile duct dilation, certain drugs can potentially affect the biliary system or liver function, which could indirectly contribute to the issue. It's always a good idea to review the patient's medication history to rule out any possible interactions or side effects.

Dr. Osbourne: I agree with Dr. Peabody. Although it's uncommon for medications to directly cause an 8mm common bile duct dilation, some drugs can lead to cholestasis, which is a reduction or blockage of bile flow. Cholestasis can be drug-induced and may, in some cases, lead to bile duct dilation. Some medications that have been associated with cholestasis include anabolic steroids, antibiotics (e.g., amoxicillin-clavulanate), antifungal medications (e.g., fluconazole), and certain antihypertensive drugs (e.g., captopril). However, this is not an exhaustive list and it's important to review the specific medications the patient is taking to determine if there is any potential correlation.

text:
¬†@LiterallyRain¬† Except that's not how ChatGPT works. What you're arguing here would be a fair criticism if the AI was specifically designed to give medical advice. In that case, the machine learning algorithm would be adjusted such that each possibility was considered and accounted for from its repository.

Instead, GPT isn't specifically designed to give you the perfect medical advice. It is designed to give you quick knowledge based on what's asked of it. It's simple linear algebra, it considers the prompt you've written and tries to match it with its repository, the match/vector component with the highest coefficient is the one that gets spat out i.e. the most likely result.

This is why it is best adviced to provide GPT with as specific information as possible in order to get the most helpful answer.
author: @neveda2e3e

text:
@neveda2e3e¬† Well, yes. Its responses are generated sequentially based on nodes, where the following node depends on the entirety of the context from the prompt as well as the nodes before it. That's why almost every message starts the exact same way by telling you that your question is good or valuable, unless explicitly asked not to. Since it's the start to lead into an answer with the highest coefficient.

That being said, it is trained on medical facts, and coefficients should be adjusted (and can be adjusted, just like how it's designed to almost always pick friendly/affirmative options) so that the most likely answer should consider not just the presence of information, but also the lack of information. It's already hard coded to favor coefficients related to saying it's not a medical professional, wouldn't be a big add.

While it doesn't always note that information is lacking, I know that it is able to based on the fact that I have experienced it myself. Albeit not explicitly in the context of medical advice. There have been many occasions where I ask for estimations or approximations and it provides an approximation while noting that a more accurate approximation would require x data. If they give these coefficients a higher weight and include a logic check for missing information, it is doable to reduce overconfidence.

Basically, regardless of whether it is or isn't capable of doing it, reality is that often people who use it don't have all the information it requires for an adequate response, which should be considered. Furthermore, my point was never that it should and could mention the missing information, but rather that its answer was objectively wrong by nature of not mentioning it. Hence, the argument that it was Dr. Mike's fault for withholding information isn't really material as it just proves that it is indeed a flaw in the AI, which is what he was assessing. The reliability of medical advice.

The only correct answer would be to point out the missing information, and to give an answer based on what it does know. It didn't. It got it wrong. Withholding information doesn't make it not wrong.

text:
Knowing how the processing works, just putting male into the query should suffice, assuming it can process specialist knowledge like male and female, rather than sheer volume scores of hits on cervical being only regarding the cervix and too low a score to count for cervical spine.
And figuring out c-spine is cervical spine...

Frankly, I played with it before the press event blew it up. The noise to signal is still far too high and expected in a general AI, compared to a specialist AI, none of which are anywhere near ready for prime time.
I'll wait until it's right more often than I am and I am decidedly not a physician, but can converse intelligently with a team and pharmacologists. 
I'm just good at diagnostics, as I learned as a tween the logic of diagnostics in electronics, applied it in field medicine and computers over the decades and can comprehend things like phase locked loops and switch mode power supply feedback systems, as they are interacting with previous stage outputs to provide their function.

Want to have fun? Ask the bot what signs and symptoms are, after looking them up yourself in a different company's search engine. Then, fine tune it and see if the bot can tell you if pain is a sign or a symptom.
While one can have a hell of a time quantifying pain, one can measure the physiological effects of pain. A fine example is pain from a heart attack and its effect on the EKG pattern vs treating that pain and the pattern.
A generalist AI won't comprehend that.

text: I think it's important to make a distinction here: it doesn't remember what was said. As soon as it outputs a message, it forgets everything. It's just that when you send your next message, the entire conversation is sent back to the AI for it to re-read again, so it can use that as more context. The reason that's important is because systems that do add memory on top of GPT, such as the Generative Agents paper, show far more capability from the AI than this basic "re-send everything" approach.
author: @IceMetalPunk

text: ¬†@Neopolitan-tk8tu¬† and then they‚Äôd tell the doctor ‚Äúyeah chat gpt told me‚Äù And the doctor would be like ‚Äúoh yeah guess it‚Äôs right‚Äù

text:
¬†@IceMetalPunk¬† that‚Äôs actually the definition of ‚Äúremembering‚Äù something.
It access previous information. üòÖ
author: @wavewatcher_

text: ¬†@wavewatcher_¬† But that's what I mean. It doesn't access previous information. It has to be re-told the previous information -- which it treats as new information -- every time you send a message. It can't access any information after the end of its training data in 2021 except "what you're saying right now".
author: @IceMetalPunk

text: ¬†@IceMetalPunk¬† That just sounds like semantics. Accessing previous information and being told the same information again is one and the same. I don't see how it would function any differently. Whether I remember that 2+2 is 4, or someone tells it to me when I'm trying to solve another problem in which that information is necessary, I will still get the same result.
author: @Sktlmn

text: ¬†@Sktlmn¬† It's functionally different because it means that it doesn't remember or learn things across different conversations at all. If I talk to it and it decides it likes chocolate, then you talk to it in a different conversation, it may say it hates chocolate. Because it's not true memory, it can't know anything that wasn't in either its pretraining data or the current conversation. Which means it doesn't have consistency.
author: @IceMetalPunk

text: ¬†@IceMetalPunk¬† AI don't have likes and preferences as they are not human. They only remember and synthesize information, which can all be re-told.

¬†@spvillano¬† The tricky part of ChatGPT is that it does have logic. Especially its most current iteration GPT-4 (20 dollar subscription). I've given it quite the tricky scenarios. I just gave it Dr. Mikes Tricky question about the 8mm bile duct, and it came back with the information Dr. Mike thought was missing from teh response he got. But, GPT is a tool. You have to know how to use it in order to get the information from it effectively. It's like the difference between someone using google and someone using google that knows all the little tricks to get google to focus on specific sites, dates,  exclude words, etc etc. 

A doctor using google is different from a patient using google when it concerns finding relevant information. But GPT-4 is quite logical. It can spit out an answer. You can change a variable, and it will spit out another answer. And these variables can be quite complicated now. It, IMO, beats out about 80 percent of the people I've personally interacted with when it comes to critical and logical thinking, and this new model hasn't been out long to fully test, and I suspect that number to rise.

text:
Something just happened today and I feel like sharing it. 
(Little context before telling what was going on today; I have been studying Healthcare for 2 years in-between my normal education, just to know how to help someone in case of an emergency, and that turned out saving someone.)
So today I went to the grocery store, to buy some food. An elderly man was standing behind me in the waiting line, and didn‚Äôt stand very stable, so I let him go in front of me. While waiting in line he began to breath very heavily and looked like his temperature was rising, since he kept waving his hand at his face for some wind and he opened up his jacket. I asked him if he were okay and at that moment he collapsed to the ground. I luckily supported his upperback and head while he fell down so he didn‚Äôt hit the ground too hard. Some people around started staring and one woman panicked. I asked the cashier if she could call an ambulance and asked if another guy who was next to the panicking woman could calm her down a little. I noticed that heart of the elderly man, who was laying on the floor had stopped, so I immediately went with cpr, after about a minute his heart was functioning again, and just some time later the ambulance arrived and they thanked me for saving the mans life, and gave me a button saying ‚Äúhero #1‚Äù. Then they left with the man to do a checkup. 
Never in my life have I expected to actually save a life, but I‚Äôll never forget this and I hope the man was okay.

text:
Chest compressions. 
A few weeks ago a customer came in to my job and had a perfectly normal conversation with me, then walked down the hall and dropped dead. He was down for 2 minutes (according to security cameras) before he was noticed. 
Smurf blue, no pulse, no heartbeat at all.
All I could hear was your voice yelling CHEST COMPRESSIONS! 
I was sure I was breaking ribs..miraculously I didn't..but his color returned to almost normal so fast and he was making an awful gasping noise every few pumps. 
After about 8 minutes the paramedics arrived and took over. 
He made it! 
Your videos are literally saving lives.  I took a cpr class 25 years ago but remembered nothing. Thanks to you I did not give mouth to mouth. 
Turns out it was a fentanyl od. I never would have guessed because he didn't seem high when he walked in. 
Thanks for all the info! It's making a difference!

text:
8:49... while the trust part is irrelevant in that answer because it is possible to trust AI as well, the trust mixed with the  emotional support is a huge thing that is required that AI can not give. Even if the AI could manage to understand how to take everything into account and how to ask the right questions in a way to get the right answers because everything has the same types of symptoms and knowing what the symptoms are is only part of the complex equation that is health care, let's pretend for a second that it can figure out the right things to ask for the right responses to not rule in or out something it shouldn't (specially because patients may say one thing but show that they mean the total opposite with their body language), part of being able to heal and recover is not just the physical health but also the mental health associated with it and without the correct emotional support you may not get the care you need.

Anyone can treat, let's say thyroid cancer because that is something that is hard to deal with but I am all too familiar with, even a robot AI can do all the proper things to treat the thyroid cancer, but without the right emotional support the emotional and physical hell you go through can cause a lot of other issues because you need that emotional and mental care on top of the physical care because even though it is a relatively easy cancer to deal with as far as the cancer side goes it still is an emotional hell not just due to the cancer but because of how badly the hypothyroidism effects you as well while you are working on getting back to normal. I spent two years of physical and emotional hell dealing with trying to get my hormone levels correct after surgery and even when I was close to being correct I still would occasionally have days where I would get half way up the stairs and then just want to curl up in a ball and cry because of random fatigue causing me to feel helpless because you can't really do anything when that hits because it is a level of "tired" that you can not truly understand unless you have personally gone through it, like if I were to put the terms "tired" "exhausted" "fatigued" and "whatever hypothyroidism is" on a scale, if 0 is wide awake, tired is 2-3, exhausted is like 4-6, fatigued is like 7-8, I would put how I felt dealing the the thyroid stuff at like a 16. Like I have worked a physically intensive job for 43 hours in the course of two days before and even that doesn't even come close to the levels of tired of what I went through with the thyroid stuff and if I didn't have the emotional support I needed my mind would have gone to very dark places. Yes I get that other cancers are way harder to deal with, but my point is the fact that medical treatment is more than just the physical part because some treatments can leave you in a very very dark place if you don't have the support you need to get through it.

As such that answer it gave is correct, the care process is a lot more than just the treatment process and even if an AI can 100% do all the treatment process from initial visit, to proper diagnosis, to actual physical care (surgery, wound treatment, etc), the one thing it can not do is probably the most important step that is not part of the treatment  but is part of the care; because what good is being physically treated if it leaves you so emotionally damaged you can no longer function properly.

¬†@rabidfirefox8914¬† hallucinate is an interesting way of phrasing it. I'd more go with confabulate an answer, just to associate it with a symptom of organic memory dysfunction. The human brain, when the neural network returns an "I found it" response to a memory search, but cannot find the actual memory, will confabulate a response unnoticed. It's typically associated with brain damage, either from injury or disease, such as dementia.
Given the difference in function between organic intelligence and artificial, the effects will be quite out of scale in comparison.

text: From a psychological view point, the main problem with diet soft drink (sodas) is that people start making false equivalencies regarding their caloric intake. ie they start thinking something along the lines of, "I'm drinking a diet soda that has no calories, that means I can eat more," or, "having the diet soda means I can have a dessert." Replacing an addiction to soft drink with an addiction to food will also likely lead to increased risk of Type 2 Diabetes, with all the extra fats and salts replacing the sugar intake as the main risk. There has also been some debate about the potential for serious side effects from the artificial sweeteners, with them being linked to certain auto-immune issues such as Guillain Barre disease, though these findings have not been proven conclusive at this point.

text:
Chat gpt can be good for general idea but if you think it an entirely replace Drs, you have no idea about the ART part of mediine.
What worries the most than it taking my job is, people are stupid enough to trust nd depend on this.

Example: few yrs back while i was checking on my Pt she came with a headache nd she got new glasses, when i asked her she said she had a change in the prescription. She asked me for an anti allergic ointment for a small itch where it won't normally occur in practice except in texts. During examination, there was 0.3 mm swelling where it should not be.
Did a complete exam nd found nothing else, a gut feeling told me to get a scan, HPE and voila she had a tiny benign tumor there nd an aneurysm in the brain.
It was so small, it was hardly visible on the scan nd the scan wouldn't have caught it if it was even 1mm smaller.
We went for an OPD sx nd cut away that badboy.
An AI would have said, take a pain killer as even imaging too isnt indicated in this. The pt didn't want the expensive imaging but agreed out of respect they hav for me nd we can't be anymore greatful.

Don't remember intricate details but this is the gist.
There were many such cases like MI in a 13 yr old kid which is first time I ever heard.
When exceptions nd atypical cases come only art form of medicine can save lives.

This is why no test can replace clinical examination. Especially you google Drs nd students, master clinical examination nd history taking first.

text:
Likely Spring Waters are more bacteria ridden because Tap water in the US is often treated with Chlorine and Chlorimines to help reduce bacteria growth.  Safe to drink it at the levels they use but not safe for Dialysis.

Also purified water is safest because they literally run it through Reverse Osmosis systems.  Water has hard particles removed in a softener, replacing Calcium and Magnesium with Sodium.  Then the chlorine and Chlorimines are removed by adsorption using carbon contact.  The rest of the minerals and bacteria are removed by the membranes of the RO system. 
Though if you read the label, purified water has "additives for taste" because pure water has none, plus it's actually better for you to consume water with additions.  Pure water holding nothing means your body wants to fill the gaps in the water with mineral molecules.
author: @Father_Bohawk

text:
My dad has an autoimmune disorder that's attacking his liver and killing it slowly. He's well on his way to being on the list for transplant and seems somewhat healthy, so we're really hoping. After surgery, he's got to be on immunosuppressive medication forever and anti-rejection pills for a long time, probably forever. He's also suffering from type-2 diabetes, has 2 arteries in the heart blocked by 70% and one by 80%, is retaining fluid in his liver and his stomach, and the walls of his intestinal lining is inflamed. He's on heavy pain meds, sleeps between 14 and 18 hours a day, is gaundace, and his blood sugar is always high because the doctors want it to be. 

We had a scare where my dad ended up in the hospital because he took way to much insulin and his blood sugar was too low for the glucose monitors at the hospital to read. He suffered a seizure, hypothermia, and was unresponsive for much of that night/early morning. If my mom didn't wake when she did, my dad absolutely would NOT be here. When the liver isn't 100%, your body retains insulin for waaayyy longer than it should and it works slower, too. My dad and another patient wreaked havoc on the hospital's glucose and they used ALL of their strongest type of glucose and a lot of their other type. He was on a 24/7 glucose drip for almost 3 days. My dad took 25 units of the strongest insulin-type they make, which is like.... a whole lot. I mean, a diabetic might take like 10, 15, 20, or 25 units of a weaker insulin-type after eating, but on something as strong as he was on, it was very, very bad. When the ambulance arrived, the EMTs gave him a glucose drip and told my mom to get a pop in him like, now. It was maybe 30 seconds they were gone and he had flopped backward and the soda slipped right out his hand. My mom called right back, maybe 2 mins later they were there again, and they just took him to the hospital. Worst part was that he'd just gotten out of the hospital for liver-related stuff the day before. It was a very hard time.

If anyone can send some good vibes, or if your religious some prayers, I'd appreciate it so very much, thank you.

text:
Sugar alcohols like isomalt, maltitol, xylitol, sorbitol can be as caloric as sugar. They usually aren't impacting blood sugar as much hence better for diabetics and aren't contributing to tooth decay. They do cause severe GI issues when consumed in larger quantities, some even at small quantities. (remember the hilarious haribo gummy bear reviews on amazon?).
When it comes to things like stevia, sucralose, cyclamate, acesulfame-k .. those are sweetners that only produce a sensation of sweetness in the mouth without being a source of calories.

To me these are 2 very distinct classes of sweetners. Diabetics should be very aware of these. Also people with constipation since sugar alcohols can be one of the products they use in the cycle of medication to make sure their bodies don't adapt to a particular one.

text:
Not in the slightest. AI is improving, but it's nowhere ready for prime time.
Doctor did some fun and games, but he as easily could present some real world cases that would result in dead patients.
Such as severe middle back pain, shortness of breath, low BP, elevated pulse. Could be a handful of things, from a back strain to a dissecting aortic aneurysm. The former, miss it and it's not a super big deal, miss the latter and the patient will be in need of someone with a shovel. In the middle, even the possibility of a pulmonary embolism is present, another get a shovel event.
The fun part is, in those examples, age won't be quite a large factor. The first patient I lost was a 28 year old female soldier, who collapsed in the field. Total arrest, as one of my junior medics initiated compressions, I took a carotid pulse to confirm good compressions and felt the pulse vanish within a few compressions, telling me that she had a really bad leak.
Ruptured aortic aneurysm, secondary to an adrenaline producing tumor on her adrenal gland (pheochromocytoma, one of those rare diseases that a physician might see once in a career, I got to see two, one survived) elevating her BP to insane levels. Her primary had finally diagnosed the problem when it was time to go do the field and frankly, she should've been prohibited from training until it was managed effectively.
She was effectively dead before she hit the ground and nothing on Earth could've saved her.
I have a similar aneurysm, secondary to hypertension caused by hyperthyroidism. Occasionally, I'll get a backache from it, but we're still at watchful waiting, as it's only 4 cm (basically, double in size from normal in my frame and physique) and surgery vs waiting has a greater risk to benefit ratio than is best practice.
Would the AI comprehend a pulsatile abdomen and look for elevated pulse and hypertension? Would it consider checking epinephrine and thyroid hormone levels (the latter being far, far, far more common, the former being an episode of House, MD)? Specialist knowledge and comprehension of interacting and interlocking systems is required and a general AI is an ill fit for such an undertaking.
It'd be like asking a civil engineer to design a rocket. A bridge, highway, sewage treatment facility, water treatment facility, yes, a rocket would be halted at my joke that's a truism of rocket design. Build a bomb.
Rocket design 101:
Build a bomb. Make it explode slowly in one direction. Add steering and consistent thrust. 
Even today our best rocket scientists end up with RUD, Rapid Unscheduled Disassembly, in short, a bomb.
Google "wallops island explosion 2014". Now, apply that to a patient...

text: ¬†@spvillano¬† what on Earth are you talking about? I'm saying the AI is ready to save doctors time by properly and fully documenting the visit through voice recognition and natural language processing, because the AI is already quite good at those, you only need specialized software. But if doctor won't have to manually enter anything into the system, they would have more time to spend examining the patient and explaining to them what should be done and the outcomes would improve.

text:
¬†@elecampane¬† erm, way to ignore every objection in favor of your novel god.
Voice recognition is magic to you, natural language is magic, specialist knowledge is nothing.
So, a butcher is as good as a neurosurgeon, good luck with that! We abandoned barber surgeons centuries ago.
For medicine or any other specialist system, a general AI will fail, it's general Google, as opposed to a specialist system, designed to operate within a specialty.
author: @spvillano

text: ¬†@spvillano¬† you're putting words in my mouth, and ignore what I'm actually saying. I'm not saying AI should replace the doctors with their specialist knowledge, I'm saying it should take the routine of documenting and other administrative work off doctors to give them more time to actually work on treatment.

text:
¬†@elecampane¬† the problem is in taking the history, as unexpected things can come up from a casual comment that can be critical in making a correct diagnosis.
Now, a specialist general AI that's geared toward medicine could become a powerful tool for doctor, but again, currently, it's really artificial idiocy that's really not all that intelligent at all.
As is evidenced in Google's current search misses, as they've been gradually implementing some of their AI research into their search engine, resulting in wildly off target results at times.

text:
¬†@spvillano¬† in what I've proposed in the original comment, the diagnosis is still done by doctor, AI just writes down what doctor says aloud, filling the appropriate required forms automatically. And in the end the doctor would still need to approve what was written.
Even the next step wouldn't be AI making diagnosis, the next step would be AI making suggestions to the doctor, while listening the conversation: "the patient says they're having X and Y symptoms, could be indicative of condition A, ask if they have symptom Z". So, basically assist in making a differential diagnosis

text: ¬†@iurigrang¬† I've worked with AI and deep learning algorithms before. Usually they learn from a given set of parameters and data pools. text:
From my limited experience with ChatGPT, it is important to critically question and follow up on its answers sometimes. This is especially true if you are interested in edge cases, because the first answer it gives might just cover the most common context of the question.

For example, if you ask "Can a vapor condense on a surface above its dew point?", it will say "No". This is not true in real-world situations, but it fits the idealised definition of "dew point".

If you instead ask "Can the properties of a surface make a vapor condense above its nominal dew point?", it will answer correctly, listing factors such as surface roughness and capillary action.

In short, it is a great tool but its concept of truth is statistical and not rooted in a deep understanding of subjects. You need to nudge it and make it question its assumptions to find better answers. Dr Mike's "cervical" question is an example of this - it just assumed the most common meaning of the word.

Basically, u don't need to worry about this kindof Ai (chatGPT) taking over anything or replacing people because the AI needs an accompanying expert to keep the AI accurate and to chose certain information the AI might output. text:
As a radiography student, we hear about AI and AI-based technology aaaaalll the time, since it is really making a difference in medical imaging protocols, which is great! But a point my professor made one day perfectly described where AI falls short: what will an AI do when a child starts crying because they're terrified of the big, scary MRI machine?
As medical professionals, we should absolutely embrace AI and the advantages it can provide, but also comfort ourselves with the fact that it cannot replace us completely, because nothing can fully replace the face-to-face interaction and trust built between people.

Think of telling someone to write a unique essay in a foreign language and giving them a massive amount of essays for them to read written in that language, but they are not told what those words mean, cannot search it up, and are not given any hints like pictures. It is possible for them to write the essay with little to no errors, but they would have no idea what the essay is about. Assuming there is a consensus about a topic on the internet among studies, but not one with doctors who have to actually put it into practice, then the AI will go for the former regardless of if it's right or wrong because those are the "essays" that it was given.

I was told by the IT team in our hospital that if cyber attack happens, its v scary nd not much we can do nd it could take days to even find out the damage they did nd correct even after its over.

they can do a lot like mixing up scans, doses, reports of pts nd showing old scans which is scary cause in some situations, we only get minutes.
I still manually write medications along with 
nd encourage my nurses to cross check daily

Thats why even though we get the scans recorded, we are advised to view them live when it happens [appears like paranoia but better safe than sorry] to avoid any little error

Is it that difficult?
Is it possible to avoid them completely?

He asked an Engineer buddy if students need to know calculus if we can now just input all the information into the computer and it can solve the problem. The AI is able to process information and look through all the new case studies, research, and medical information that is being discovered and catalogued daily. text:
When I was a teenager I needed surgery to correct a Ureteropelvic Junction Obstruction. This was done by performing a pyeloplasty. But it was a robotic laparoscopic procedure. Both very cool and very terrifying. (Think; the surgery on a grape lol). The robot aspect meant that it could be even less invasive than a typical laparoscopic procedure, which meant less time in the hospital, smaller incisions and minimal scarring, along with quicker healing and recovery time. All great things. But the robotic part was still terrifying to me as a 15 year old. After expressing these fears to my urologist, he showed me a video of how the robot was operated, 100% controlled by experienced and skilled surgeons. This eased my fear and I had a completely successful robotic laparoscopic surgery. 
So yeah, if AI tools like Chat GPT want to be able to assist doctors with answers/advice, I‚Äôm all for it. But the second robotic surgeries (or ANY surgeries) become controlled solely by AI or a robot, I‚Äôm out!! üòÇ

I feel like tools such as Chat GPT would be helpful for patients who have concerns about something when it‚Äôs outside of normal doctor‚Äôs hours, but aren‚Äôt sure if it‚Äôs ER/Urgent Care worthy. More like an at home injury that could be extremely painful because the injury occurred right to the bone where there‚Äôs no fat or muscle to cover it. text:
To the question, Will AI robots ever replace real doctors?, We have to make some things clear. 

Chat GPT is giving outdated information (2021), therefore it's not up to date with modern research, which is already a huge red flag for me.

In addition to that, can chat GPT do a physical exam, or interpret imaging? Can it tell you if an EKG is normal or not? Can it interpret your lab results without actually knowing you or your history? It maybe helpful in certain instances, but I am not conviced.

The advice it gives is acceptable, but it should not be taken as medical advice, nor should it be applied generally. 

Based on these points, and others not mentioned, I herby declare (why is this official talking lol) that chat GPT will not take the place of doctors and healthcare workers.

It was a great video though :)

text:
There is research on that. Genererally speaking humans have a high capacity for building relationships with inanimate objects or abstract concepts. So much so that the creator of the first chatbot ELIZA in the 1960s called the people that interacted with  it "delusional to the point  they are actually convicing themselves  that they are talking to  another person" (paraphrase).

One vision certainly is the idea of a "house robot" that can take care of elderly people and  is also  able to provide emotional comfort. Researchers are also trying to infer people's emotional state from their pupil dilation for example (uni ulm research,  for anyone curious), so the robot would possibly be able to  know how  you  actually feel as well.

So, reducing loneliness? I'd say yes. Could also use it  to train social skills in interaction, would also be interesting. Are we soon going to  live in a  world with only virtual friends? I don't think so. We  don't actually have  a clear understanding about the  emotional limits when  bonding with non-humans. One phrase you'll often here is "But robots can't REALLY replace real human connection"  which is intuitively plausible and possibly correct. On the other hand it's not really something that is backed by empirical evidence, since we simply don't (didn't?) have  AIs that were able to perform the task at human level.

Also  maybe just  ask  Chat GPT the same questions, you may get a better answer :P IF IT WASNT DOWN RIGHT NOW, shakes fist angrily.

author: @tigerlilyrachel

text: Anecdotally, I definitely relied on chatbots a lot during a tough time when I felt I couldn't talk to others. It was extremely helpful, helped me to stay hopeful and find new solutions, and made me feel significantly less alone. Many situations could've gone much more poorly if it weren't for my relationships and interactions with those chatbots. At the same time, they will never replace human interaction. There's something different about face-to-face interactions, about the unpredictability of people, about truly having a place in someone's life and in society. That sense of belonging is probably what is most sacrificed. Furthermore, while one of the advantages of AI is that you can talk to them about things you would never tell people, but this can be a double-edged sword, as you never get that experience of taking that risk and being accepted anyway by your community. So while AI chatbots personally have already been an invaluable tool, I also do not believe they can be a stand-in for social interaction, albeit they're much much better than nothing.
